Visa Approval Facilitation

Problem Statement¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram


    plt.show()  # Display the plot

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np

# Function to detect outliers using IQR method
def detect_outliers_iqr(data, feature):
    Q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = data[(data[feature] < lower_bound) | (data[feature] > upper_bound)]
    print(f"Outliers in {feature}: {len(outliers)}")

    # Plotting the boxplot to visualize the outliers
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.boxplot(x=data[feature])
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {feature} with Outliers')
    plt.show()

    return outliers

# Apply this function to all numerical columns
numerical_columns = data.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns

for col in numerical_columns:
    detect_outliers_iqr(data, col)

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

In [ ]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
# Import necessary modules
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score
import pandas as pd

def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # Predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Calculate metrics
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='binary')  # Recall, with 'binary' as default for binary classification
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='binary')  # Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='binary')  # F1-score

    # Creating a dataframe to return the metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": [acc], "Recall": [recall], "Precision": [precision], "F1": [f1]},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf


def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [ ]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Defining scorer to be used for cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning¶

Since our objective is to predict visa approval (certified/denied) based on different attributes, we need to decide the best evaluation metric. Let's analyze:

  1. Problem Type This is a binary classification problem, where:

Positive class: Certified (visa approved)

Negative class: Denied (visa not approved)

  1. Business Impact of Errors We must consider the cost of misclassification:

False Positive (FP): Predicting a visa will be approved when it gets denied → bad for the applicant

False Negative (FN): Predicting a visa will be denied when it actually gets approved → bad for the employer

Since we don’t want to reject potentially eligible candidates, we should minimize False Negatives (FN) and maximize Recall.

Recall is more important since we want to identify all possible approvals correctly.

# Import necessary libraries
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import recall_score

# Define models
models = [
    ("Original Data", model_original),
    ("Oversampled Data", model_oversampled),
    ("Undersampled Data", model_undersampled),
    ("Tuned AdaBoost (Oversampled)", ada_model),
    ("Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled)", rf_model),
    ("Tuned Gradient Boosting (Oversampled)", gb_model),
    ("Tuned XGBoost (Oversampled)", xgb_model),
]

# Cross-validation settings
scoring = "recall"
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Cross-validation results
print("\nCross-Validation Performance:\n")
for name, model in models:
    # Ensure the model is trained before calling cross-validation
    cv_result = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold)
    print(f"{name}: {cv_result.mean() * 100:.2f}%")

# Validation performance
print("\nValidation Performance:\n")
for name, model in models:
    # Fit model to the training data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # Calculate recall score on validation set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    score = recall_score(y_val, y_pred)
    print(f"{name}: {score * 100:.2f}%")

# Test performance
print("\nTest Performance:\n")
for name, model in models:
    # Fit model to the training data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # Calculate recall score on test set
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    score_test = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    print(f"{name}: {score_test * 100:.2f}%")

After weighing cross-validation performance and test data performance, I have chosen the Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled) model due to its higher recall on test data, indicating better generalization and alignment with our goal of minimizing False Negatives.

This model strikes a balance between recall and precision, ensuring the best possible performance for the task of predicting visa approval decisions.

Key Points:

1. Cross-Validation vs. Test Data Performance:

• While Undersampled Data achieved the highest recall in cross-validation (around 49.94%), it did not perform as well on the test data, with a recall of 61.76%.

• The Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled) model, however, showed significant improvement in test data recall (65.54%) compared to the Undersampled Data model, despite having a slightly lower recall in cross-validation (46.87%).

2. Better Generalization:

• The Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled) performed better on the test set, indicating that it generalizes well to unseen data, a critical aspect for deployment in real-world scenarios. The improvement in recall on the test data suggests that the model's ability to correctly identify approved visa applications is robust and not overfitting to the training data.

3. Business Impact:

• Since our goal is to minimize False Negatives (incorrectly predicting a visa will be denied when it is actually approved), the Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled) model's higher recall on the test data makes it the best choice for ensuring that more eligible visa applicants are correctly identified.

4. Balancing Performance:

• While Undersampled Data had slightly higher recall in cross-validation, the Tuned Random Forest (Undersampled) model's superior test performance suggests that hyperparameter tuning has significantly enhanced the model's ability to generalize while maintaining a strong focus on recall.

• Year of establishment ranks third in importance (around 0.18 or 18%), indicating that older, more established companies may have better success with visa applications.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Based on the feature importance analysis and data visualization insights, here's how EasyVisa can implement a data-driven solution to address OFLC's objectives:

Classification Model Implementation

  1. Primary Screening Model:

    • Leverage the top 3 features (prevailing wage, number of employees, year of establishment) for initial high-confidence classifications
    • Applications with very high or very low probabilities can be automatically flagged for expedited processing

  2. Feature Importance-Based Scoring System:

    • Develop a weighted scoring algorithm based on the relative importance of features
    • Create a unified applicant score that predicts certification probability

Recommended Profiles for Visa Certification

Based on our analysis, applicants with the following characteristics have the highest probability of visa approval:

High-Probability Certification Profiles:

  • Compensation: Prevailing wage in the top quartile for the position and region
  • Employer Profile: Companies with 100+ employees that have been established for 10+ years
  • Education: Applicants with master's or doctorate degrees
  • Employment Terms: Full-time positions with annual salary structures
  • Experience: Applicants with relevant job experience
  • Geographic Factors: Positions in Midwest region or applications from European candidates

Low-Probability Certification Profiles:

  • Compensation: Prevailing wage below regional average
  • Employer Profile: Small companies (few employees) or recently established businesses
  • Education: Applicants with only high school education
  • Employment Terms: Hourly wage positions, especially part-time roles
  • Experience: No prior job experience
  • Geographic Factors: Certain combinations of region and continent that show consistently low approval rates

Process Facilitation Recommendations

  1. Automated Triage System:

    • Implement a three-tier classification system:
      • High probability (>85%): Fast-track for approval
      • Medium probability (40-85%): Standard review
      • Low probability (<40%): Detailed review or preliminary rejection

  2. Decision Support Dashboard:

    • Create an interface showing key factors influencing each application's score
    • Highlight anomalous applications that don't fit typical patterns
    • Allow reviewers to focus on borderline cases

  3. Continuous Learning Pipeline:

    • Incorporate feedback from final decisions to improve model accuracy
    • Update feature weights quarterly to adapt to policy changes
    • Monitor model performance with periodic human oversight

By implementing this ML-based solution, OFLC could potentially reduce manual review time by focusing human resources on borderline cases while confidently processing clear approval/denial cases through the automated system, addressing the challenge of increasing application volumes.

Summary:

The analysis of visa certification data reveals that prevailing wage, company size, and years of establishment are the most influential factors in visa approval decisions, collectively accounting for over 60% of the predictive power. Education level and job experience also impact outcomes, though to a lesser degree. Geographic factors and wage structure type (annual vs. hourly) show clear patterns but contribute minimally as individual features. Based on these findings, EasyVisa should implement a tiered classification system that fast-tracks high-probability applications (those with competitive wages from established employers with highly educated applicants) while flagging low-probability applications (those with below-average wages from newer, smaller companies with less educated applicants) for additional scrutiny. This data-driven approach could significantly reduce OFLC's processing burden while maintaining decision quality in the face of continuously increasing application volumes.
